[PlyCount "1"]
[GameId "2180482214504521"]

1. Z0 {Hello everyone! Welcome to my second opening mini-course for White! After tackling 1...[e5] with the Gunsberg variation, the time has come to recommend a system against the French Defense. We will investigate the Advance variation of the French Defense where I will recommend my pet line on the sixth move: 6. [Na3]. There are many advantages to choosing this variation: - This rare and poisonous move scores well in practice. In the recommended lines, White scores between 55 and 60% most of the time. - The recommended variation is low on theory. Understanding plans and ideas is more important than knowing concrete lines. You can play it with confidence after just a few hours of study. - Your opponent will often be out of theory just as we are beginning ours! - You will learn many common strategic and tactical patterns that will improve your knowledge and that can be used in different types of middlegame and endgame positions. - You will improve your understanding of playing on color complex and the importance of activity over materialism. To help you with your study, I included a chapter entitled Key Middlegame Themes & Plans where I did my best to give an overview of the roles of the pieces and pawns in this variation and the common tricks and traps you must know. You will also find model games throughout the course to help you develop a strong understanding and feeling for the type of positions we are aiming for. The course is for everyone even though players in the 1400-2200 FIDE rating range are the main target audience. The recommended lines are sound and recent recommendations in Lifetime Repertoires on the French Defense are all tackled. Naturally, I also recommend how to face my recommendation in my previous course The Aggressive French. As with my previous courses, I want to emphasize the importance of understanding over memorizing countless lines. Please spend more time understanding the key ideas of the recommended system and practicing them in your games rather than learning all the moves by heart. The goal is to make chess simple for you, but complicated for your opponents. I'm convinced studying the recommended lines will help you improve your ratings and more importantly your chess understanding. Happy studying!} *

[Event "Dynamite 1.e4: Advance French for White"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Overview"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C02"]
[PlyCount "15"]
[GameId "2180482214680650"]

1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The Advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} (4... Qb6 5. Nf3 Bd7 {5...[Nc6] will transpose into our mainline.} 6. Na3 $5 {Whenever possible, we will meet Black's tries with our poisonous knight. This is no exception. We will continue with all of our typical ideas.}) 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {The main move. Black immediately puts more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} (5... Bd7 {Black often starts with this move order before deciding what to do with their queen. This is of no importance to us as we will bring the game into our territory with our next move:} 6. Na3 $5 {And we will continue with all of our typical ideas.}) (5... cxd4 {This capture is premature as it frees the natural [c3]-square for White's knight.} 6. cxd4 Nge7 7. Na3 $5 {But who said we care about natural squares? Let's continue with our typical ideas instead!}) (5... Nge7 {Black wants to develop the knight on [f5] and put pressure on [d4]. Any idea about how we will continue?} 6. Na3 $5 {Of course! We will continue with our typical ideas.}) (5... f6 {This premature move is an exception as we will not put our knight on [a3] this time. Instead, we will fight for control over the [e5]-square with our next move.} 6. Bb5 {And White will have excellent prospects.}) (5... Nh6 {This is the recommended move in my course The Aggressive French. It is possible to take a slight advantage by following a computer line recommended by Giri in his Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's 1. [e4] − Part 2. However, this line seems to me unpractical for both sides. Instead, I will recommend staying into our territory by going for a move we are very familiar with:} 6. Na3 {And again, we will continue with all of our typical ideas.}) 6. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c2,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Be3g4,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {[%cal Rf8a3] Black's main choice by far.} 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bxa3 $6 {A responsible choice. Black concedes us all the dark-squares in exchange for damaging our pawn structure.} (7... Bb4+ {Before taking any decision, Black throws this check to force our bishop on the [d2]-square.} 8. Bd2 {This will leave the [b2]-pawn unprotected. Black will have to accept the challenge and take it. But this will cost them time in development!} Bxa3 {The main continuation in games of amateurs. I consider this move dangerous as it surrenders to White the control over all the dark squares. (8...Nge7 Giri's recommendation in his French LTR. 9.Nc2 We will continue with our plan. 9...Bxd2+ 10.Qxd2 If Black doesn't grab the [b2]-pawn now, it will happily be pushed to [b4] to seize space on the queenside. 10...Qxb2 11.Bd3 We continue our development and are ready to castle next. We have great compensation for the pawn: - Our rooks will come on the b- and c-files. - If Black doesn't prevent it, our queen will jump on [g5] and provoke weaknesses. - Black will have trouble putting their king into safety. As we will see, our [c2]-knight will pose lots of problems from [e3]. 11...Qb6 It is also possible for Black to start with 11...[h6]. But it doesn't change much 12.O-O We are ready to continue with [Rab1] and [Rfc1]. Our [c2]-knight will come to [e3] next with lots of attacking potential against Black's kingside. You will find more about the key ideas in those typical positions in thechapter Key Middlegame Themes & Plans and throughout the course. ) (8...Nxd4?? A common blunder. 9.Nxd4 Qxd4 10.Qa4+ And Black loses material on the next move. )} 9. bxa3 {Black has to accept the challenge and capture our [d4]-pawn as we are threatening to continue with [Rb1] next.} Nxd4 {The right continuation. White's score in this position is excellent after our next move:} 10. Qa4+ {We will continue our development with [Bd3] next. We have ideas such as [Qg4] to attack the [g7]-pawn and provoke even more weaknesses on the dark squares. We will also bring our rooks on [b1] and [c1]. White is down a pawn but Black's position is already difficult to handle. White's score is over 60% in those positions.}) ({After} 7... Nge7 {, 7...Bd7 , and 7...Nh6 , we usually play 8.Nc2 and continue with our typical ideas.}) 8. bxa3 {[%csl Ra3,Ra2,Gc1,Gd1,Gf3][%cal Ga3f8,Gh4d8] In exchange for a damaged pawn structure on the queenside, we obtained domination over all the dark squares and will get an important lead in development. Black will have to be careful to survive such positions.} *

