1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {[%csl Rc8] The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} (4... Bd7 {This will transpose into our lines with ..Qb6 + ...Bd7 or ...Nc6 + ...Bd7.}) 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {Black's most common move amongst amateurs. Black uses their queen to put more pressure against the [d4]-pawn.} (5... cxd4 6. cxd4 Nge7 7. Na3 {And we are back into our territory.}) 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} (6... Bd7 7. Nc2 {and we are back into our territory.}) 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bxa3 $6 {A responsible choice. Black concedes us all the dark-squares in exchange for damaging our pawn structure.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Gc1,Ra3,Ra2,Gf3,Gd1][%cal Ga3f8,Gh4d8]} Nge7 9. Bd3 {[%cal Gb1h7,Ga1b1,Ge1g1] Black can't castle because of the Greek gift. Black's position is already difficult to handle.} Bd7 {After this move, the [d4]-pawn is under attack.} ({The blunder} 9... O-O {is the second most common move in this position. Black is doomed after} 10. Bxh7+ Kxh7 11. Ng5+ {and the queen will come either on h5 or d3.}) 10. Rb1 {We gain a tempo and indirectly defend the [d4]-pawn as Black's queen is forced to move.} Qa5+ {[%csl Ra3]} 11. Bd2 ({The simple and most practical solution. White also has excellent play after both} 11. Kf1 {and 11.Qd2 .}) 11... Qxa3 {[%csl Ra2,Rd3]} 12. Qe2 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge1g1] We are going to [e2] as the [b1]-square is already taken by our rook.} (12. Qe2 {Other moves such as 12. Rb3 are also possible, but this is the best one as Black can't take the a2-pawn with} Qxa2 {because after} 13. O-O {Black's queen is in trouble. For instance, the game could continue:} Qa4 14. Bb5 Qc2 15. Rfc1 {We mobilize all of our pieces while the queen is losing time.} Qg6 16. Bd3 Qh5 17. Rxb7 {and White is much better.}) 12... b6 {Black protects their b-pawn.} (12... Nf5 {is tempting, but this leaves the b7-pawn unprotected.} 13. Rxb7 Ncxd4 {The next sequence is forced:} 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Qe3 Nf5 16. Bxf5 Qxe3+ 17. Bxe3 exf5 {Everything was forced up to this point.} 18. Bc5 {White is down a pawn but has more than compensation thanks to the rook on the seventh rank, a safer king, and complete control over the dark squares.}) 13. O-O {[%csl Ra3][%cal Gb1b3] We continue with our quick development. The [f1]-rook will come to the c-file while the other may be lifted along the third rank if needed.} Ng6 {The most common move. Black makes room on [e7] for their queen, but the knight is misplaced on [g6] and invites our next move:} (13... O-O {A common mistake.} 14. Rb3 Qxa2 15. Bxh7+ Kxh7 16. Ng5+ {And Black is doomed.}) 14. h4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh4h5,Yf1c1] We are threatening to harass the knight with [h4]-[h5]. From there, the pawn will also have the opportunity to be pushed until [h6]. We are also ready to bring the [f1]-rook on the c-file. White already has an important advantage.} *

