the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} (4... Bd7 {This will transpose into our lines with ..Qb6 + ...Bd7 or ...Nc6 + ...Bd7.}) 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {Black's most common move amongst amateurs. Black uses their queen to put more pressure against the [d4]-pawn.} (5... cxd4 6. cxd4 Nge7 7. Na3 {And we are back into our territory.}) 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} (6... Bd7 7. Nc2 {and we are back into our territory.}) 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bxa3 $6 {A responsible choice. Black concedes us all the dark-squares in exchange for damaging our pawn structure.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Gc1,Gf3,Gd1,Ra3,Ra2][%cal Ga3f8,Gh4d8]} Nge7 9. Bd3 {[%cal Gb1h7,Ga1b1,Ge1g1] Black can't castle because of the Greek gift. Black's position is already difficult to handle.} Nf5 {This is premature.} 10. Rb1 {We develop our rook with tempo and reduce the pressure against the [d4]-pawn.} Qa5+ 11. Bd2 {We sacrifice this pawn as usual.} Qxa3 {[%csl Rd3]} 12. Rb3 $1 {Not the only move, but the best one! We are going for full activity and want to play against Black's misplaced queen.} ({If you don't like the following recommendation, it is possible to continue with} 12. Qe2 {followed by 13. O-O with our typical ideas.}) {However, I find the following line about non-materialism very instructive and can't prevent myself from showing it:} 12... Qxa2 13. O-O {[%cal Gd2c3] If Black does nothing concrete, our next move will be [Bc3].} Nfxd4 {Black accepts the challenge and grabs the [d4]-pawn.} 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Rb4 {We attack the knight with tempo and are ready for the rook lift!} Nc6 16. Rg4 {Black is up three pawns, but its position seems scary. Can they also take the [e5]-pawn?} Nxe5 {[%csl Rg4,Rd3]} ({The engine also recommends to continue with} 16... g6 {, but that weakens the dark squares and invites our bishop on g5 and f6.}) 17. Bb1 {We escape the fork by gaining a tempo on Black's queen.} Qa1 18. Rg3 {[%csl Rg7,Re5][%cal Gd2c3,Gd1e1] Black's position is close to undefendable for humans, even though they are 4 pawns up. We have a great domination on the dark squares and they will be forced to give back material if they want to survive.} *

