1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {[%csl Rc8] The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} (4... Bd7 {This will transpose into our lines with ..Qb6 + ...Bd7 or ...Nc6 + ...Bd7.}) 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {Black's most common move amongst amateurs. Black uses their queen to put more pressure against the [d4]-pawn.} (5... cxd4 6. cxd4 Nge7 7. Na3 {And we are back into our territory.}) 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} (6... Bd7 7. Nc2 {and we are back into our territory.}) 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bxa3 $6 {A responsible choice. Black concedes us all the dark-squares in exchange for damaging our pawn structure.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Gc1,Gf3,Gd1,Ra3,Ra2][%cal Ga3f8,Gh4d8]} Qa5+ {Black wants to provoke a concession.} 9. Bd2 {We are ready to sacrifice a pawn for activity. We should always remember that we have a long-term compensation of the dark squares for the missing pawn.} Qxa3 10. Qb1 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gd3b5,Ge1g1,Gf1c1] A multi-purpose move we are already familiar with from our chapter on the Key Middlegame Ideas. From [b1], the queen puts pressure on [b7], helps with the development of the light-squared bishop on its best diagonal, and also helps with ideas such as [Bb4] if Black's knight leaves [c6].} Nge7 {Black continues their development.} 11. Bd3 {[%cal Bf1c1,Ge1g1]} ({The most natural and logical. Although the engine recommends} 11. Bb5 {, it seems more practical to continue with our typical ideas. For example, the game could continue:}) 11... h6 {Black prepares themselves to castle kingside on the next move.} 12. O-O {[%cal Gf1c1]} O-O 13. Rc1 Nf5 {The [d4]-pawn is taboo because of the [Bb4]-threat once Black's knight leaves the [c6]-square.} 14. Rc3 {A strong multi-purpose move. The rook can help for a kingside attack in the future. At the same time, we prepare to take full control over the c-file.} Qe7 15. Qb2 {[%cal Ga1c1] The [d4]-pawn is still taboo because we can take on [c8] and recapture on [d4] next.} Bd7 16. Rac1 {With full control of the board. The [d4]-pawn is still taboo, let's see why:} Nfxd4 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. Be3 Nc6 19. Bc5 {And Black loses the exchange.} *

