the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} (4... Bd7 {This will transpose into our lines with ..Qb6 + ...Bd7 or ...Nc6 + ...Bd7.}) 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {Black's most common move amongst amateurs. Black uses their queen to put more pressure against the [d4]-pawn.} (5... cxd4 6. cxd4 Nge7 7. Na3 {And we are back into our territory.}) 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} (6... Bd7 7. Nc2 {and we are back into our territory.}) 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxa3 $6 {The second most common continuation in games of amateurs. I consider this move dangerous as it surrenders to White the control over all the dark squares.} 9. bxa3 {[%cal Ga1b1] Black has to accept the challenge and capture our [d4]-pawn as we are threatening to continue with [Rb1] next.} Nxd4 {The right continuation. White's score in this position is excellent after our next move:} 10. Qa4+ Nc6 11. Bd3 {[%csl Rg7,Gd3,Gd2][%cal Ge1g1,Ga1b1,Ga4g4] We continue with our developement. We are ready to continue with [O-O], [Rb1], [Rfc1], [Qg4], etc. Black's position is already difficult to handle and White score over 60% in those positions. Let's see how the game could continue after Black's three most common moves:} Bd7 $6 {Not a good move, but the most common one in practice.} 12. Qg4 {[%csl Rg7] And White has the upper hand. For instance, the game could continue:} g6 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7,Rh6,Gd2] This move weakens the dark squares even more.} 13. Rb1 Qc7 {[%csl Re5,Rb7]} 14. O-O {[%cal Gf1c1]} Nge7 15. Rfc1 $16 {And Black's position is already close to undefendable.} *

