king to safety or to continue their queenside development. While the computer claims the position is equal, I’m convinced we have the more comfortable side of equality.} b6 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gc8d7] Black protects their b-pawn and prepares ...[Bd7].} 15. Ne3 $1 {[%cal Ge3g4,Re8g8,Be3f1,Bf1g3,Bg3h5] Let's take a stock here. The position is equal according to the computer. But can we say the same when humans are playing against each other? Black can't castle on the kingside for now as [Ne3]-[g4] would be crushing. Hence, Black is doomed to passivity by playing slow and improving move on the queenside. In the meantime, White has two plans to improve their position: [Ne3]-[g4] or [Nf1]-[g3]-[h5]. It is also possible to play slow/waiting moves such as [h3], [h4], etc. to ask Black what he wants to do. In practice, I'm more than confident about White's chances to play for a win!} *

