1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {[%csl Rc8] The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} (4... Bd7 {This will transpose into our lines with ..Qb6 + ...Bd7 or ...Nc6 + ...Bd7.}) 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {Black's most common move amongst amateurs. Black uses their queen to put more pressure against the [d4]-pawn.} (5... cxd4 6. cxd4 Nge7 7. Na3 {And we are back into our territory.}) 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} (6... Bd7 7. Nc2 {and we are back into our territory.}) 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bd7 9. Nc2 {We continue with our plan and ask Black's bishop a question.} Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Qxb2 11. Bd3 Qb6 {[%cal Rh7h6]} 12. Qg5 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Ge1g1]} ({Of course, continuing with} 12. O-O {and our typical ideas is also possible. We exploit the fact Black didn't have enough time to cover the g5-square. Our goal is to provoke weaknesses in Black's position after moves such as} g6 {or ...Kf8 . We are ready to castle on the next move.}) 12... Qa5+ {Black exploits our last move and forces our king to stay in the center.} 13. Ke2 {[%cal Gg5f4,Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Gh1b1,Ye2f1,Yf1g1]} (13. Ke2 {We keep the rooks connected. The king is safe as the center is closed. Black is forced to weaken their position with either} g6 {or Kf8 . We are ready to continue playing on the kingside with ideas such as Qf4, h4-h5, etc. At any moment, we can improve the safety of our king with Rhb1 followed by Kf1-g1.}) *

