1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {[%csl Rc8] The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} (4... Bd7 {This will transpose into our lines with ..Qb6 + ...Bd7 or ...Nc6 + ...Bd7.}) 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Bd7 {Black starts to develop their bishop first before deciding where their queen belongs. While this move order can matter depending on White's setup, our next move immediately brings the game into our territory.} 6. Na3 $5 {As usual, we are going for our poisonous move.} cxd4 (6... Qb6 {With a transposition. For instance, the game could continue:} 7. Nc2 cxd4 8. cxd4 Nb4 9. Ne3 $1 {And we are back into a line we will study later in the course.}) 7. cxd4 {[%cal Ga3c2]} Bxa3 {This is quite similar to our lines where Black's queen is on [b6].} 8. bxa3 Nge7 9. Bd3 {We continue our development.} Qa5+ ({The logical} 9... Qb6 {is well met by} 10. Rb1 Qa5+ {where White can continue with either 11. Bd2 or 11.Kf1, which were covered in the first chapter.}) 10. Bd2 {This is a typical pawn sacrifice. We have enough compensation on the dark squares for the pawn.} (10. Qd2 {is a possible alternative.} Nf5 {The most precise continuation.} 11. Rb1 b6 12. Bb2 Qxd2+ {Kxd2 with equal chances.}) 10... Qxa3 11. Qb1 {[%csl Rh7,Rb7][%cal Ge1g1,Bf1c1] We protect the [d3]-bishop before castling on the kingside. We are ready to continue with our typical ideas. Black's position is already difficult to handle in practice. Our next moves are [O-O] followed by [Rc1]. In the main course, we delve deeper into this line and analyze how to counter GM Saša Martinović's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire.} *

