the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} (4... Bd7 {This will transpose into our lines with ..Qb6 + ...Bd7 or ...Nc6 + ...Bd7.}) 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Nge7 6. Na3 $5 {Poisonous knight!} Nf5 (6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Nf5 8. Nc2 {And we are ready to continue with our typical ideas.}) 7. Nc2 cxd4 8. cxd4 {And we are ready to continue with our typical ideas. For instance, the game could continue:} Qb6 9. Bd3 {We continue our development as the [d4]-pawn is tactically protected.} Bd7 {Black prevents any check on the [a4]-[e8] diagonal and may think the [d4]-pawn is now under attack.} 10. O-O {We complete our development and set a trap.} Nfxd4 {Black falls for a common trap you will get many times in your games.} 11. Nfxd4 Nxd4 12. Be3 {Black's queen is pinned.} Bc5 {This move only helps briefly as we can continue with:} 13. b4 {And Black loses a piece.} *

