1. Z0 {We will first investigate the two main routes our [a3]-knight will take during the games.} *

[Event "Dynamite 1.e4: Advance French for White"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Ne3-Ng4 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1bq1rk1/pp2npp1/2n1p2p/3pP3/3P4/3B1N2/P1NQ1PPP/1RR3K1 w - - 0 15"]
[PlyCount "13"]
[GameId "2180482215323744"]

{This position is taken from the course and serves as a demonstration of one of the routes our [c2]-knight can take to create problems for Black's king.} 15. Ne3 $1 {[%cal Ge3g4] A good move. As we will see with the next informational variation, there are two routes the knight can use from [e3] to help with the attack against Black's monarch. In this first example, we will see the first idea which is to bring the knight to the [g4]-square.} b6 {Black often plays this move to protect the b-pawn before developing the light-squared bishop. This is too slow, but Black's position is already difficult anyways. Let's continue with our idea:} 16. Ng4 $1 {[%cal Gg4h6,Gg4f6] From [g4], the knight is threatening to sacrifice itself on [f6] or [h6] to ripe open Black's king.} Bd7 {For instance, the game could continue:} 17. Nxh6+ gxh6 18. Qxh6 {[%csl Gf3,Gd3,Gh6][%cal Gc1c3,Gb1b3] Our three pieces will be enough to deliver checkmate. In some positions, we may need to invite additional pieces to the attack. In such cases, we should always consider bringing the rooks into play via the third rank.} f5 19. exf6 Nf5 20. Qg6+ Kh8 21. Ng5 {And Black can resign. Remember: [Na3]-[c2]-[e3]-[g4] is one of the two maneuvers we have at our disposal.} *

[Event "Dynamite 1.e4: Advance French for White"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Ne3-Ng4 #2"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C02"]
[PlyCount "61"]
[GameId "2180482215340129"]

{Here is a model game with light annotations to give you an idea of how our [a3]-knight can become a powerful attacking unit.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Na3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Nge7 9. Nc2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Qxb2 11. Bd3 Qb6 12. O-O h6 13. Rab1 Qd8 14. Rfc1 O-O 15. Ne3 {[%cal Ge3g4] The knight is going to [g4].} Nf5 {Black would love to exchange knights on [f5]. But this is not the plan!} 16. Ng4 {[%cal Gg4f6,Gg4h6] The position is already difficult for Black who must take into account all types of sacrifices on [h6] and [f6] now.} Nce7 17. Rb3 $1 {[%cal Gb3c3,Gc3g3,Gg3h3] We will talk about this idea later in this chapter. White is ready to double rooks on the c-file or to use it as an attacking unit after bringing it to [g3] or [h4].} b6 18. Rbc3 Bd7 19. Rc7 Rc8 20. Rxa7 Rxc1+ 21. Qxc1 Nc6 {White's rook is under attack. What to do?} 22. Bxf5 {Offense is the best defense!} exf5 (22... Nxa7 23. Nxh6+ Kh8 {(23...gxh6 24.Qxh6 exf5 25.Ng5 and Black has to give up their queen. )} 24. Ng4 exf5 25. Nf6 Re8 26. Qg5 gxf6 27. Qh6+ Kg8 28. exf6 {and Black is doomed.}) 23. Nxh6+ (23. Nf6+ {was best.} gxf6 24. Qxh6 {And Black is doomed.}) 23... gxh6 24. Qxh6 Nxa7 25. Ng5 {And Black has to give up their queen.} Qxg5 26. Qxg5+ Kh7 27. Qe7 Rc8 28. Qxf7+ Kh8 29. h4 Rc7 30. e6 Rc1+ 31. Kh2 {Black resigns.} 1-0

[Event "Dynamite 1.e4: Advance French for White"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Ne3-Ng4 and Ne3-f1-g3-h5"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/1pq1npp1/p1n1p2p/3pP3/3P4/3B1N2/P1NQ1PPP/1RR3K1 w kq - 0 15"]
[PlyCount "11"]
[GameId "2180482215356514"]

{Here is another example about the knight maneuver.} 15. Ne3 $1 Bd7 (15... O-O {This is premature. We can jump immediately on [g4] as in our previous informational variation:} 16. Ng4 {Black is lacking defenders on the kingside.} Nf5 17. Bxf5 exf5 18. Nf6+ $1 {It is also possible to capture on [h6]. But let's take the opportunity to show a variation with a sacrifice on [f6]. Both moves are thematic and should always be considered as candidates in your calculations.} gxf6 19. Qxh6 fxe5 20. Qg5+ Kh7 21. Qh4+ Kg7 22. Qg3+ {And Black's king feels terrible. We will take on [e5] next with the knight and bring more pieces in the attack with [Rc3] next.}) 16. Nf1 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gf1g3,Gg3h5] This is the second key maneuver. The idea is to bring the knight to [h5] via [f1]-[g3]-[h5]. This will put pressure on the [g7]-pawn and also give us sacrificial idea such as [Nf6]+!} O-O {Now that our knight left the [e3]-square and can't jump on [g4] immediately, Black can allow themselves to castle kingside. Still, they are playing into our hands.} 17. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3h5] We continue with our plan. Note: It is also possible to come back on [e3] and jump on the [g4]-square next.} Rac8 18. Nh5 {[%cal Gh5g7,Gh5f6] Our knight finally arrives on [h5]-square. Let's see different possibilities:} Be8 {[%cal Gf7f5,Rf7f6,Rf6f5] Black would like to continue with either ...[f6] or ...[f5].} (18... Ng6 {Black tries to bring a piece into the defense. But this does nothing against our plan:} 19. Nf6+ Kh8 {Taking on [f6] would lead to similar play as in our mainline.} 20. g4 $1 {We are going for the kill and want to continue with [g4]-[g5] next. We should never be scared of losing the [f6]-knight as the attacking ratio is in our favor. A pawn on [f6] would be as good as a piece, by the way.}) (18... Kh8 19. g4 $1 {With similar ideas.}) 19. Nf6+ $3 {But we prevent their idea!} gxf6 20. Qxh6 {And Black is doomed. Remember: We can also use the route [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to create attacking chances against Black's king. We are not scared of sacrificing it at some point to open lines against the enemy's monarch. And we should always keep the idea of the pawn lever [g4]-[g5] on our list.} *

[Event "Dynamite 1.e4: Advance French for White"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "...Nb4 Well Met by Ne3"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r3kbnr/pp1b1ppp/1qn1p3/3pP3/3P4/5N2/PPN2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 0 8"]
[PlyCount "2"]
[GameId "2180482215372899"]

8... Nb4 {There are a few variations where Black tries to exchange their knight for our [c2]-knight.} 9. Ne3 $1 {[%cal Ga2a3] We should always decline it. Our knight is more useful than Black's knight, and we need it to create attacking chances against Black's king in the future.} *

