1. Z0 {Next, we will investigate common tricks & traps everyone should be familiar with.} *

[Event "Dynamite 1.e4: Advance French for White"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Nxd4?? #1"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1b1k1nr/pp3ppp/1qn1p3/3pP3/1b1P4/N4N2/PP1B1PPP/R2QKB1R b KQkq - 0 8"]
[PlyCount "4"]
[GameId "2180482215393381"]

{This is a position from the course that you will reach many times in your games. The [d4]-pawn seems en prise. Can Black take it?} 8... Nxd4 {This capture has been played in 30000 out of 50000 games!} 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Qa4+ {[%csl Rb4] Oops! And Black loses material on the next move.} *

[Event "Dynamite 1.e4: Advance French for White"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Nfxd4?? #2"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r3kb1r/pp1b1ppp/1qn1p3/3pPn2/3P4/3B1N2/PPN2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 b kq - 0 10"]
[PlyCount "6"]
[GameId "2180482215405670"]

{Here is another position from the course with a common mistake by Black committed in 52% of the games.} 10... Nfxd4 {Black thinks the [d4]-pawn is free. But this is not the case!} 11. Nfxd4 Nxd4 {But now comes:} 12. Be3 {[%csl Rb6] And Black's queen starts to feel uncomfortable.} Bc5 {Unfortunately for Black, this does not work as we can push our b-pawn forward:} 13. b4 $1 {And Black loses a piece. This is a common tactic than can occur in many variations. So it is important to be aware of it!} *

[Event "Dynamite 1.e4: Advance French for White"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "The d4-pawn Is Often Taboo - Advanced Example"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1b2rk1/pp3pp1/2n1p2p/3pPn2/3P4/q2B1N2/P2B1PPP/RQR3K1 w - - 0 14"]
[PlyCount "7"]
[GameId "2180482215422055"]

{Now, let's see a more advanced example of the hanging [d4]-pawn. Those examples will help you to understand there is no need to panic when your [d4]-pawn is under attack. More often than not, Black can't take it or you will get compensation for it!} 14. Rc3 {White kicks the queen with tempo and prepares to double on the c-file or lift the rook to the kingside.} Qe7 {The only square.} 15. Qb2 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gb2d4] White wants to double on the c-file next. The [d4]-pawn is tactically protected as after:} Nfxd4 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Rxc8 {[%cal Gb2d4] White's queen is ready to recapture on [d4].} *

[Event "Dynamite 1.e4: Advance French for White"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "g4 Trap"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C02"]
[PlyCount "29"]
[GameId "2180482215438440"]

1. e4 {Here is a Blitz game I played where we will talk about another common trap.} e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nge7 6. Na3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Nf5 8. Nc2 Be7 9. Bd3 Qb6 10. O-O {Black can't take the [d4]-pawn.} O-O {And now comes:} (10... Nfxd4 11. Ncxd4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Bb5+ {And Black loses their queen. One of the basic traps in the French Defense everyone should know.}) 11. g4 {Black can't take on [d4] because of the basic trap we saw in the previous note.} Nh4 {We should always stay alert after this move:} (11... Nh6 {is well met by} 12. Kh1 {when we are ready to continue with 13. Rg1 next.}) 12. Nxh4 Bxh4 13. g5 $3 {[%cal Gd1g4,Gg4h5] And the [h4]-bishop is trapped! We are ready to continue with either [Qg4] or [Qh5].} Qd8 14. Qh5 g6 15. Qxh4 {And Black can resign.} 1-0

