[Event "Dynamite 1.e4: Advance French for White"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Qg5"]
[Result "*"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r1b1k2r/pp2nppp/2n1p3/q2pP3/3P4/3B1N2/P1NQ1PPP/R4RK1 w kq - 0 13"]
[PlyCount "2"]
[GameId "2180482215594100"]

{Black wants to exchange the queen. Should we accept?} 13. Qg5 $1 {Of course not! Instead, we put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. Black is already forced to make concessions with moves such as ...[Kf8], ...[Ng6], or ...[g6]. Jumping on [g5] with the queen is quite thematic. Black will often play ...[h6] to take the [g5]-square under control and avoid shenanigans. Let's see why:} Ng6 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5] The only move, but not a pleasant one to make. This invites White to harass the knight with the [h4]-[h5] we already talk about.} (13... Kf8 {Black will struggle to put their king to safety and connect the rooks.}) (13... g6 {This causes too many problems on the dark squares.} 14. Qf6 {We are ready to continue with typical ideas such as [Ne3]-[g4]-[h6], etc.}) (13... O-O 14. Bxh7+ {Never forget about the Greek gift sacrifice!} Kxh7 15. Qh5+ Kg8 16. Ng5 {And Black is doomed.}) *

[Event "Dynamite 1.e4: Advance French for White"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Key Middlegame Themes & Plans"]
[Black "Sacrifice of the a3 Pawn With Bd2 vs Qa5+ & Qb1"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C02"]
[PlyCount "49"]
[GameId "2180482215606389"]

{This is a Blitz game I played.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Na3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Bxa3 {When you see this move on the board, never forget you just became grandmaster of the dark squares!} 8. bxa3 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 {This is a common pawn sacrifice. We have enough compensation thanks to our control over the dark squares and lead in development.} Qxa3 10. Qb1 $1 {This is the instructive move I want you to remember. From [a3], Black's queen prevents us from developing our light-squared bishop to its best diagonal. With this move, we prepare [Bd3] and create pressure against the b-pawn.} a6 11. Bd3 {[%csl Rh7]} Qa4 {[%csl Rd4] Black attacks the [d4]-pawn. Should we be afraid?} 12. O-O {[%csl Gf3,Gf1,Gd2,Gd3,Gb1,Re8] No! We have enough compensation to sacrifice another pawn. I'm convinced the lines recommended in this course will help you better understand the importance of activity over material.} Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Rc1 {[%cal Gc1c7] Bringing another piece into play and inviting Black to grab another pawn!} Ne7 (14... Qxe5 {This is too dangerous.} 15. Qb6 {Black will not survive the attack on the dark squares.}) 15. Bc3 Qf4 16. g3 Qg5 17. h4 Qg4 18. Bb4 {[%cal Re8g8,Gb4d6] Preventing Black from castling kingside and improving the bishop's position.} Ng6 19. Rc7 {Taking control over the 7th rank.} Bd7 20. Bxg6 {Getting rid of Black's only minor piece which can control some dark squares.} hxg6 21. Rxb7 Rxh4 22. Bd6 Qe4 23. Rb8+ Rxb8 24. Qxb8+ Bc8 25. Qxc8# {1-0. Throughout the course, we will see more variations where we use this [Qb1]-idea.} 1-0

