with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {The main move. Black immediately puts more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bxa3 $6 {The second most common continuation in games of amateurs. I consider this move dangerous as it surrenders to White the control over all the dark squares.} 9. bxa3 {[%cal Ga1b1] Black has to accept the challenge and capture our [d4]-pawn as we are threatening to continue with [Rb1] next.} Nge7 $6 {The second most common move. Let's see why allowing us to continue with [Rb1] is not ideal for Black:} 10. Rb1 {We develop our rook with tempo.} Qc7 11. Bd3 {[%csl Gb1,Gd3,Gd2,Gd1,Gf3,Rh8,Re8,Rc8,Ra8,Rc7] We continue our development and are ready to castle kingside next.} Nf5 {Black attacks the [d4]-pawn. But who cares?} 12. O-O {Our lead in development is massive and Black is in big trouble.} O-O 13. Qc2 {[%csl Rh7,Rf5,Rc7][%cal Gg2g4,Bf1c1,Rc6d4] We apply pressure along the [b1]-[h7] diagonal and indirectly defend the [d4]-pawn. We are ready to continue with [Rfc1] and/or [g4].} Qe7 {[%cal Rf5h4,Rg2g4] Black wants to meet our [g4] idea with ...[Nh4]!} 14. Rb3 $3 {[%cal Rf5d4,Rc6d4,Gb3g3,Gg3h3,Bc2c3] We are ready to bring the rook on the kingside. If necessary, the queen can help defend the [d4]-pawn by coming on [c3]. But for now, the [d4]-pawn is not comestible.} Nfxd4 $4 {Let's see what happens if Black falls for our trap:} 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Bxh7+ {We are winning an important pawn and are making room for our heavy pieces on the h-file.} Kh8 17. Qd1 {[%cal Gb3h3,Gd1h5] The queen is rerouted to [h5] via [d1] while the rook can join the attack via [h3].} Kxh7 18. Rh3+ Kg8 19. Bb4 {[%csl Rd4,Rf8,Rg8] And Black is doomed.} *

