1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {The main move. Black immediately puts more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Nge7 {Giri's recommendation in his French LTR.} 9. Nc2 ({If you want to surprise an opponent following Giri's recommendation,} 9. Nb5 {and 9.Bc3 should be explored. But this is the move I like best.}) 9... Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 {[%cal Gb2b4] If Black doesn't grab the [b2]-pawn now, it will happily be pushed to [b4] to seize space on the queenside.} Qxb2 (10... O-O {, 10...Bd7 and 10...Nf5 are well met by b2-b4 with an advantage for White.}) 11. Bd3 {[%cal Ge1g1,Yd2g5,Ga1b1,Gh1c1,Bc2e3,Be3g4,Be3f1,Bf1g3] We continue our development and are ready to castle next. We have great compensation for the pawn: - Our rooks will come on the b- and c-files. - If Black doesn't prevent it, our queen will jump on [g5] and provoke weaknesses. - Black will have trouble putting their king into safety. As we will see, our [c2]-knight will pose lots of problems from [e3].} Qb6 ({It is also possible for Black to start with} 11... h6 {. But it doesn't change much.}) 12. O-O {[%cal Ga1b1,Gf1c1,Bc2e3,Ye3g4,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5] We are ready to continue with [Rab1] and [Rfc1] while our [c2]-knight will come to [e3] next with lots of potential on Black's kingside.} h6 {[%csl Rg5] Black takes control over the important [g5]-square.} 13. Rab1 {[%cal Gf1c1,Gc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Ye3g4] We are ready to continue with all of our typical ideas. For instance, the game could continue:} Qd8 14. Rfc1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Rc8d7] Let's take a stock. In exchange for one pawn, all our pieces are active and ready to apply pressure on both wings. In the meantime, Black's position seems already difficult to handle in practice. It’s not so simple for them to get their king to safety or to continue their queenside development. While the computer claims the position is equal, I’m convinced we have the more comfortable side of equality.} O-O $2 15. Ne3 $1 {[%cal Ge3g4,Yg4h6,Yg4f6]} Nf5 {Black attacks the [d4]-pawn.} (15... b6 16. Ng4 $1 {with lots of deadly threats. We already analyzed this position in detail in the chapter Key Middlegame Themes & Plans.}) 16. Ng4 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gc1c3] But we can continue with our plan as the [d4]-pawn is tactically protected. Black's position is difficult to handle. Our [g4]-knight is annoying while we can prepare a rook lift with [Rc3] next.} (16. Ng4 {For instance, the game could continue:} Kh8 17. Rc3 {We continue with our plan.} Ncxd4 {Black fell for greediness!} 18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19. Bc2 {We are making room for the rook.} Nf5 {Black tries to get the knight back into the defense. (19...Nxc2 20.Rh3 with tremendous pressure on h6. )} 20. Rh3 {But now comes our rook. Black is lost as we put too much pressure on h6.}) *

