re you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Nge7 {Giri's recommendation in his French LTR.} 9. Nc2 ({If you want to surprise an opponent following Giri's recommendation,} 9. Nb5 {and 9.Bc3 should be explored. But this is the move I like best.}) 9... Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 {[%cal Gb2b4] If Black doesn't grab the [b2]-pawn now, it will happily be pushed to [b4] to seize space on the queenside.} Qxb2 (10... O-O {, 10...Bd7 and 10...Nf5 are well met by b2-b4 with an advantage for White.}) 11. Bd3 {[%cal Ge1g1,Yd2g5,Ga1b1,Gh1c1,Bc2e3,Be3g4,Be3f1,Bf1g3] We continue our development and are ready to castle next. We have great compensation for the pawn: - Our rooks will come on the b- and c-files. - If Black doesn't prevent it, our queen will jump on [g5] and provoke weaknesses. - Black will have trouble putting their king into safety. As we will see, our [c2]-knight will pose lots of problems from [e3].} Qb6 ({It is also possible for Black to start with} 11... h6 {. But it doesn't change much.}) (11... O-O 12. O-O Qb6 {will transpose.}) 12. O-O {[%cal Ga1b1,Gf1c1,Bc2e3,Ye3g4,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5] We are ready to continue with [Rab1] and [Rfc1] while our [c2]-knight will come to [e3] next with lots of potential on Black's kingside.} O-O 13. Rab1 {[%cal Gf1c1,Gc2e3,Ye3g4,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5]} Qa5 {If the queen retreats on [c7] or [d8] instead, we can play [Ne3] and the related ideas as in our mainline.} 14. Qe2 {[%cal Gc2e3,Gh2h4] We avoid the queen trade and keep the [e3]-square for our knight.} *

