1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {The main move. Black immediately puts more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bb4+ 8. Bd2 a6 {This is the recommendation in LTR: Plitcha's French Defense.} 9. Nc2 {This leaves us time to retreat our knight on [c2] and ask a question to Black's dark squared bishop.} Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Qxb2 {Ambitious! Black has to be careful now.} 11. Bd3 {[%cal Gd2g5,Ge1g1] We continue our development. We are ready to continue with [O-O] and always keep [Qg5]-idea in mind.} h6 {Plitcha's recommendation. Black immediately takes the [g5]-square under control.} 12. O-O Qb6 {It is time to retreat the queen.} 13. Rab1 Qc7 (13... Qd8 14. Rfc1 {with similar ideas.}) 14. Rfc1 {Our typical continuation in these types of positions.} Nge7 15. Ne3 $1 {[%csl Rf6,Rg7][%cal Ge3f1,Gf1g3,Gg3h5,Ye8g8,Ye3g4] Take a stock here. The position is equal according to the engine. Black is up a pawn but White has compensation thanks to their lead in development and safer king. In practice, the position looks difficult for Black as they must adopt a passive type of play. Black can't castle on the kingside because of [Ng4] followed by the [Nf6]+ idea to damage the defense of their king with a massive attack. Hence, they are forced to play slowly with improving moves on the queenside before they can think of safeguarding their king. From [e3], we also have our typical idea of rerouting the knight to [h5] via [Nf1]-[g3]-[h5] to pose practical problems against the [g7]-pawn. For instance, the game could continue:} Bd7 {[%cal Re8g8] It's possible to play waiting moves to meet ...[O-O] with [Ng4] or to continue with [Nf1]-[g3]-[h5].} 16. Nf1 {[%cal Gf1g3,Gg3h5] This is the other plan at White's disposal.} O-O (16... Nf5 17. g4 Nfe7 18. Ng3 {and Black will have trouble castling kingside due to the g5-push.}) 17. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3h5,Gh5f6] The knight is going to [h5] next and Black will have to calculate the sacrifice on [f6] each time they want to make a move. The position is equal according to the engine. But I'm convinced mere mortals will prefer the White side.} *

