1. e4 e6 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 3. e5 c5 4. c3 Nc6 5. Nf3 Qb6 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bb4+ 8. Bd2 Bd7 9. Nc2 {We continue with our plan and ask Black's bishop a question.} Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Qxb2 {Black has to accept the challenge or we will continue with [b4].} 11. Bd3 {We continue our development.} Qb6 {[%cal Rh7h6]} 12. Qg5 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Ge1g1]} ({Of course, continuing with} 12. O-O {and our typical ideas is also possible. We exploit the fact Black didn't have enough time to cover the g5-square. Our goal is to provoke weaknesses in Black's position after moves such as} g6 {or ...Kf8 . We are ready to castle on the next move.}) 12... Qa5+ {Black exploits our last move and forces our king to stay in the center.} 13. Ke2 {[%cal Gg5f4,Bh2h4,Bh4h5,Gh1b1,Ye2f1,Yf1g1]} (13. Ke2 {We keep the rooks connected. The king is safe as the center is closed. Black is forced to weaken their position with either} g6 {or Kf8 . We are ready to continue playing on the kingside with ideas such as Qf4, h4-h5, etc. At any moment, we can improve the safety of our king with Rhb1 followed by Kf1-g1.}) *

