with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {The main move. Black immediately puts more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bxa3 $6 {A responsible choice. Black concedes us all the dark-squares in exchange for damaging our pawn structure.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Gc1,Ra3,Ra2,Gf3,Gf1][%cal Ga3f8,Gh4d8]} Nge7 9. Bd3 {[%cal Gb1h7,Ga1b1,Ge1g1] Black can't castle because of the Greek gift. Black's position is already difficult to handle.} Bd7 {After this move, the [d4]-pawn is under attack.} 10. Rb1 {We gain a tempo and indirectly defend the [d4]-pawn as Black's queen is forced to move.} Qa5+ {[%csl Ra3]} 11. Bd2 ({The simple and most practical solution. White also has excellent play after both} 11. Kf1 {and 11.Qd2 .}) 11... Qxa3 {[%csl Ra2,Rd3]} 12. Qe2 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge1g1] We are going to [e2] as the [b1]-square is already taken by our rook.} b6 {Black protects their b-pawn.} (12... Nf5 {is tempting, but this leaves the b7-pawn unprotected.} 13. Rxb7 Ncxd4 {The next sequence is forced:} 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Qe3 Nf5 16. Bxf5 Qxe3+ 17. Bxe3 exf5 {Everything was forced up to this point.} 18. Bc5 {White is down a pawn but has more than compensation thanks to the rook on the seventh rank, a safer king, and complete control over the dark squares.}) 13. O-O {We continue with our development and are ready to continue with our typical ideas.} Nf5 ({The only move. If Black continues with} 13... Ng6 {or 13...O-O , this will transpose to our next lines.}) (13... Qxa2 14. Ra1 Qb2 15. Rfb1 {and the queen is trapped.}) 14. Rfc1 {We put our rook on its best square. Black's queen feels awkward on [a3] while their king is a bit stuck in the center.} (14. Rfc1 {Black can try taking the d4-pawn with} Nfxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 {but after} 16. Qe3 Nf5 17. Qh3 {it will be difficult to survive.}) *

