the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bxa3 $6 {A responsible choice. Black concedes us all the dark-squares in exchange for damaging our pawn structure.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Gc1,Ra3,Ra2,Gd1,Gf3][%cal Ga3f8,Gh4d8]} Nge7 9. Bd3 {[%cal Gb1h7,Ga1b1,Ge1g1] Black can't castle because of the Greek gift. Black's position is already difficult to handle.} Bd7 {After this move, the [d4]-pawn is under attack.} 10. Rb1 {We gain a tempo and indirectly defend the [d4]-pawn as Black's queen is forced to move.} Qa5+ {[%csl Ra3]} 11. Kf1 {[%csl Rb7] Alternative. And White has the upper hand. We can continue with [Rxb7] or [h4] and our typical ideas next. Our king will be safe either on [g1] or [g2]. For instance, the game could continue:} Qc7 {The most common move to defend the [b7]-pawn.} 12. h4 {[%cal Gh1h3,Gh3g3,Gg3b3] White wants to activate their rook via [h3].} Nf5 13. Rh3 {We don't care about the [d4]-pawn!} Nfxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Qg4 {[%csl Rg7] The [g7]-pawn is under attack.} Nf5 16. Bxf5 {Now we enter an opposite-colored bishops' scenario, that will favor the attacking side.} exf5 17. Qxg7 {We grab the [g7]-pawn.} O-O-O 18. Bg5 {From [g5], the bishop block the g-file and makes room for out [c1]-rook to operate.} Rdg8 19. Qf6 {[%cal Gh3b3] And we are ready to continue with [Rh3]-[b3]. White's attack is irresistible. No one can nor should remember such a line. But it is important to be familiar with the typical ideas used there as they can be used again and again in countless other positions.} *

