[PlyCount "35"]
[GameId "2180482216712336"]

1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {The main move. Black immediately puts more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bxa3 $6 {A responsible choice. Black concedes us all the dark-squares in exchange for damaging our pawn structure.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Ra3,Ra2,Gc1,Gd1,Gf3][%cal Gh4d8,Ga3f8]} Nge7 9. Bd3 {[%cal Gb1h7,Ga1b1,Ge1g1] Black can't castle because of the Greek gift. Black's position is already difficult to handle.} Nf5 {This is premature.} 10. Rb1 {We develop our rook with tempo and reduce the pressure against the [d4]-pawn.} Qa5+ 11. Bd2 {We sacrifice this pawn as usual.} Qxa3 {[%csl Rd3]} 12. Rb3 $1 {Not the only move, but the best one! We are going for full activity and want to play against Black's misplaced queen.} ({If you don't like the following recommendation, it is possible to continue with} 12. Qe2 {followed by 13. O-O with our typical ideas.}) {However, I find the following line about non-materialism very instructive and can't prevent myself from showing it:} 12... Qxa2 13. O-O {[%cal Gd2c3] If Black does nothing concrete, our next move will be [Bc3].} Nfxd4 {Black accepts the challenge and grabs the [d4]-pawn.} 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Rb4 {We attack the knight with tempo and are ready for the rook lift!} Nc6 16. Rg4 {Black is up three pawns, but their position seems scary. Can they also take the [e5]-pawn?} Nxe5 {[%csl Rg4,Rd3] The engine also recommends to continue with 16...[g6], but that weakens the dark squares and invites our bishop on [g5] and [f6].} 17. Bb1 {We escape the fork by gaining a tempo on Black's queen.} Qa1 18. Rg3 {[%csl Rg7,Re5][%cal Gd2c3,Gd1e1] Black's position is close to indefensible for humans, even though they are 4 pawns up. We have a great domination on the dark squares and they will be forced to give back material if they want to survive.} *

