the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bxa3 $6 {A responsible choice. Black concedes us all the dark-squares in exchange for damaging our pawn structure.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Gc1,Ra3,Ra2,Gd1,Gf3][%cal Ga3f8,Gh4d8]} Qa5+ {Black wants to provoke a concession.} 9. Bd2 {We are ready to sacrifice a pawn for activity. We should always remember that we have a long-term compensation of the dark squares for the missing pawn.} Qxa3 10. Qb1 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gd3b5,Ge1g1,Gf1c1] A multi-purpose move we are already familiar with from our chapter on the Key Middlegame Ideas. From [b1], the queen puts pressure on [b7], helps with the development of the light-squared bishop on its best diagonal, and also helps with ideas such as [Bb4] if Black's knight leaves [c6].} Nge7 {Black continues their development.} 11. Bd3 {[%cal Bf1c1,Ge1g1]} ({The most natural and logical. Although the engine recommends} 11. Bb5 {, it seems more practical to continue with our typical ideas. For example, the game could continue:}) 11... h6 {Black prepares themselves to castle kingside on the next move.} 12. O-O {[%cal Gf1c1]} O-O 13. Rc1 Nf5 {The [d4]-pawn is taboo because of the [Bb4]-threat once Black's knight leaves the [c6]-square.} 14. Rc3 {A strong multi-purpose move. The rook can help for a kingside attack in the future. At the same time, we prepare to take full control over the c-file.} Qe7 15. Qb2 {[%cal Ga1c1] The [d4]-pawn is still taboo because we can take on [c8] and recapture on [d4] next.} Bd7 (15... Nfxd4 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Rxc8 Raxc8 18. Qxd4 {and Black is in trouble.}) 16. Rac1 {With full control of the board. The [d4]-pawn is still taboo, let's see why:} Nfxd4 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. Be3 {The move that was missed by Black when they captured on [d4]. We attack the knight with tempo and are ready to come on [c5] with our bishop.} Nc6 19. Bc5 {And Black loses the exchange.} *

