the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bxa3 $6 {A responsible choice. Black concedes us all the dark-squares in exchange for damaging our pawn structure.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Ra3,Ra2,Gc1,Gd1,Gf3][%cal Gh4d8,Ga3f8]} Bd7 9. Bd3 $1 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ga1b1] We sacrifice the [d4]-pawn for quick development.} Nxd4 {The next moves are as forced as they are natural:} 10. O-O Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 {[%cal Ga1b1]} Ne7 12. Rb1 Qc7 13. Qg3 {[%csl Rg7] Everything was more or less forced up to this point. Black now has to decide how to defend the [g7]-pawn.} Ng6 {The most common move but a mistake!} 14. h4 {[%csl Rg6,Rg7][%cal Gh4h5] We immediately threaten to harass Black's misplaced knight with [h5]. Black's position is already difficult to handle. Let's see how the game could continue:} Qxe5 {Black's choice in 22 out of 23 games and a mistake!} 15. f4 $1 {A good move that most players with the Black pieces don't see coming.} Qd4+ 16. Rf2 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gh4h5] It is also possible to put the king on [h2]. We are ready to continue with ideas such as [h5] and [Bb2].} O-O 17. h5 {[%csl Rg6,Rd4,Rg7][%cal Gc1b2] And Black loses a piece because of the [Bb2] threat.} Rac8 18. Bb2 Qc5 19. hxg6 {Even though Black has 3 pawns for the piece, this is not enough. They can't mobilize them, as we have good control over the central dark squares. White has a massive advantage.} *

