with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {The main move. Black immediately puts more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} cxd4 {Black's main choice by far.} 7. cxd4 {The main tabiya.} Bd7 8. Nc2 {We continue with our plan.} Rc8 $5 {[%cal Rc6b4,Rf1d3] Before jumping on [b4] with the knight, Black improves the position of their rook.} 9. Be2 $1 {We calmly continue to develop our pieces. The bishop is better placed on [e2] as we don't want to lose time moving it after 9...[Nb4].} Nb4 10. Ne3 $1 {[%cal Ga2a3,Ge1g1] This is our idea. We don't help Black to complete their development by taking on [b4]. We are ready to continue with [O-O] and push back the [b4]-knight with [a3].} Bb5 {Black's position is cramped so it makes sense to exchange some pieces, especially the bad bishop.} 11. a3 (11. O-O {is a simple solution. But I like this move better as there is a trap.}) 11... Bxe2 {Black manages to exchange their bad bishop for our good one.} 12. Qxe2 Nc6 13. O-O {[%cal Gf1d1] We voluntarily give up the [d4]-pawn to pose practical problems to Black.} Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Qxd4 15. Qb5+ {[%csl Rb7] And now, the only move for Black is quite difficult to make as the [b7]-pawn is under attack.} Rc6 $7 {The only move even though it seems quite strange to allow White taking on [b7] with tempo.} (15... Kd8 {15.Nxd5 Qxd5 17.Bg5+ and Black is doomed.}) (15... Ke7 16. Nf5+ exf5 17. Qxb7+ Kd8 18. Bg5+ {and Black is doomed.}) 16. Qxb7 Ne7 {Black protects the rook with their knight.} 17. Qb8+ {We include this check to misplace Black's knight before improving the position of our queen.} Nc8 18. Qb5 {And Black managed to equalize after a series of precise moves. In practice, no humans made the decision to put their rook on [c6]. Instead, they all put their king on [d8] and got crushed!} *

