with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {The main move. Black immediately puts more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Be3g4,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3] This is our poison! The knight is aiming for the [c2]-square from where it will help to reinforce White's center. At the same time, this move provokes Black to capture on [d4] and on [a3] next to damage our pawn structure. If this happens, Black will surrender control over all the dark squares. This will give us lots of chances to seize the initiative and create strong attacks. If Black isn't interested in damaging our pawn structure, our knight will be slowly but surely rerouted from [c2] to [e3]. From there, we will have two main maneuvers at our disposal: [Ne3]-[g4] to put pressure on [f6] and [h6] or [Ne3]-[f1]-[g3]-[h5] to put pressure on the [g7]-pawn. This will give us lots of attacking chances against Black's king. As you will see, we will often accept to sacrifice a pawn or more to obtain compensation by a lead of development or by domination over the dark squares. Black will often have to accept passivity if they want to survive our poison. White is scoring well in all the recommended lines (>55%) and I'm sure you will contribute to improving the scores even more!} Nh6 7. Nc2 {And we are back into our territory.} cxd4 8. cxd4 {It is also good to recapture on [d4] with the [c2]-knight.} Nf5 {The logical continuation.} 9. Bd3 Bd7 10. O-O Nfxd4 $4 {Black went for this mistake in most of the games.} 11. Nfxd4 Nxd4 12. Be3 {We are familiar with this typical trick.} Bc5 13. b4 Nxc2 14. Bxc5 {And Black is down material.} *

