with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {The main move. Black immediately puts more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c2,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Be3g4,Rf8a3]} a6 {This rare move has been tried in a few games. It seems like a waste of time since we weren’t planning to do anything on [b5].} 7. Nc2 {[%cal Gf1d3,Ge1g1] We continue with our plan. If Black doesn't do anything concrete, our next moves will be [Bd3] and [O-O] as usual.} Bd7 ({Both} 7... Nge7 8. Bd3 Nf5 9. O-O cxd4 10. cxd4 {and 7...cxd4 8.cxd4 Nge7 9.Bd3 Nf5 10.O-O will lead to well-known territory except Black lost time with the inclusion of ...a6.}) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gd4c5] Once our bishop is on [d3], taking on [c5] becomes a threat.} cxd4 9. Ncxd4 Nge7 (9... Nxd4 {will transpose in the mainline after} 10. Nxd4 Ne7 11. O-O Nc6 12. Nf3 {.}) 10. O-O Nxd4 (10... Ng6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. h4 {is uncomfortable for Black.}) 11. Nxd4 Nc6 {[%cal Rc6e5]} 12. Nf3 {We avoid the exchange and protect the [e5]-pawn. White already has a significant advantage thanks to their superior development and strong control over the central squares. The [e5]-pawn and the absence of a knight on Black's kingside provide excellent attacking chances in the future.} *

