1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The Advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Qb6 {The main move. Black immediately puts more pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 6. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c2,Yc2e3,Ye3f1,Yf1g3,Yg3h5,Rf8a3]} f6 {Black doesn't waste time and immediately goes for a quick breakthrough. This rare line has been tested in a few master-level games, achieving notable success for Black. However, White is more than fine if they know how to respond properly. I’d recommend that the most advanced players study this line in depth, while grasping the main ideas should suffice for everyone else.} 7. Bb5 {[%cal Yb5c6,Gf3e5] With this move, we want to fight for control over the [e5]-square. For this purpose, we are ready to imbalance the game by exchanging our bishop for Black's knight at some point.} cxd4 (7... Bd7 8. O-O cxd4 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. cxd4 c5 11. Nc2 {and White has the advantage.}) (7... a6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. O-O cxd4 10. cxd4 c5 11. Nc2 {and White has the advantage.}) 8. Nxd4 ({We are forced to recapture with our knight as} 8. cxd4 {is not good because after} Bxa3 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. bxa3 Ba6 {, White's king becomes stuck in the center.}) 8... Bxa3 (8... fxe5 9. Qh5+ {and Black loses castling rights.}) (8... Bd7 9. O-O Nxe5 {(9...Nxd4 10.Bxd7 Kxd7 11.cxd4 The position is equal according to the computer, but Black will have to be precise as their king is stuck in the center. )} 10. Re1 {And the position should be equal after} Bxb5 11. Naxb5 a6 12. Bf4 axb5 13. Bxe5 fxe5 14. Rxe5 O-O-O 15. Rxe6 Rd6 16. Re8+ Rd8 17. Qg4+ Kb8 18. Rxd8+ Qxd8 19. Nxb5 {with dynamic equality. Of course, learning such lines by heart does not make much sense. But it is always useful to see them at least once.}) 9. bxa3 Bd7 ({After the engine's recommendation} 9... Qc7 {, Black is close to equality. For instance, the game could continue:} 10. Bf4 Nge7 11. exf6 Qxf4 12. fxe7 Qe5+ 13. Ne2 Bd7 14. O-O {and Black should be fine even though the position remains complex.}) (9... fxe5 10. Qh5+ Kf8 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Nf3 $1 e4 13. Ne5 Qc7 14. Bf4 {and White has an advantage.}) 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Qg4 {[%csl Rg7,Re8][%cal Gg4h5] And White has the upper hand.} *

