[GameId "2180482217384098"]

1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Bd7 {Black starts to develop their bishop first before deciding where their queen belongs. While this move order can matter depending on White's setup, our next move immediately brings the game into our territory.} 6. Na3 {As usual, we are going for our poisonous move.} f6 {This is an interesting move and the recommendation in the Chessable course Take Down the French Advance by till.} 7. Bb5 $5 ({This is my recommendation instead of the more common} 7. Bd3) 7... cxd4 8. Bxc6 $1 {We are going for our plan.} bxc6 (8... Bxc6 9. Nxd4 {and White is already much better. The most common} fxe5 {is well met by} 10. Qh5+ {with an important advantage.}) 9. cxd4 {When Black recaptures on [c6] with the b-pawn, we should recapture on [d4] with our c-pawn to maintain control over the key central squares.} (9. Nxd4 c5 10. Nf3 {and Black is already better.}) 9... Qa5+ {The engine's recommendation.} (9... c5 10. O-O cxd4 11. Nc2 {and White is already much better.}) (9... Bxa3 {A wrong exchange.} 10. bxa3 Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qxa3 12. O-O Ne7 13. Re1 {and White is ready to continue with exf6, Rb1 + Bb4, etc.}) (9... Ne7 10. Nc2 Ng6 11. h4 h5 12. Qd3 Kf7 13. O-O {The position is equal, but White's position seems simple to handle in practice.}) 10. Bd2 Qa6 $7 {The best and only move that helps Black to equalize. While we aim to control the dark squares, they are trying to create problems on the light ones. This move has been played in two online games and both Black accounts are now closed! :} (10... Bb4 {A step in the wrong direction. After this exchange, White will dominate on the dark squares even more.}) 11. Nc2 {[%cal Gc2b4,Gb4d3] If possible, we would like to continue with [Nb4]-[d3].} c5 {[%cal Rd1e2,Rd7b5] Black prevents our plan and free the [b5]-square for their bishop.} (11... Qd3 12. Be3 Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 {with an equal endgame.}) 12. a4 $1 {[%cal Gd1e2,Rd7b5] We prevent any ...Bb5 and are ready to continue with 13. Qe2 next. The position is equal according to the engine but remains complicated for humans, especially with the Black's pieces. It would not be practical to delve deeper into this position, so I would not recommend it.} (12. a4 {But here is an example of how the game could continue:} Qc4 13. Bc3 a5 14. Na3 Qa6 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. Ne5 cxd4 17. Bxd4 {with chances for both sides.}) *

