1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Nge7 {Black starts with the development of their knight first and wants to jump on [f5] to put pressure on our [d4]-pawn.} 6. Na3 $5 {Poisonous knight!} Nf5 7. Nc2 cxd4 8. cxd4 {And we are ready to continue with our typical ideas.} Be7 {The most common continuation. Black continues their development. The drawback is that the [f5]-knight can't retreat on [e7] anymore.} 9. Bd3 {We also continue with our development.} O-O {Now Black has shown their cards, we can appreciate the drawback of their previous move:} 10. g4 {We strike immediately.} Nh4 {The natural continuation. But now comes our typical trap:} 11. Nxh4 Bxh4 12. g5 {And Black is lost as after:} Bxg5 13. Qh5 {[%csl Rg5,Rh7][%cal Gh5h7,Gh5g5] They have to defend against too many threats.} h6 14. Rg1 Bxc1 15. Rxc1 {We calmly recapture. Our strong attack on the g-file is still there.} Kh8 16. Ke2 {[%cal Gg1g3,Gc1g1] We connect our rooks and are ready to continue with [Rg3] followed by [Rcg1]. [Rxg7] is also a strong candidate move to keep in mind! Black is doomed.} *

