with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Nge7 {Black starts with the development of their knight first and wants to jump on [f5] to put pressure on our [d4]-pawn.} 6. Na3 $5 {Poisonous knight!} Nf5 7. Nc2 {And we are back into our territory.} cxd4 8. cxd4 {And we are ready to continue with our typical ideas. For instance, the game could continue:} Qb6 9. Bd3 {We develop our bishop and put some pressure against the [f5]-knight.} Bd7 {Black develops their bishop first before considering taking on [d4].} 10. O-O Nfxd4 {And Black fell for a typical trap!} 11. Nfxd4 Nxd4 12. Be3 Bc5 13. b4 {And Black is doomed.} *

