1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} Nh6 $5 {This is the recommended move in my course The Aggressive French. It is possible to take a slight advantage by following a computer line recommended by Giri in his Lifetime Repertoires: Giri's 1. [e4] − Part 2. However, this line seems to me unpractical for both sides. Instead, I will recommend staying into our territory by going for a move we are very familiar with:} 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c2,Yh6f5] Here we go again with our poisonous knight!} cxd4 7. cxd4 f6 {This rare move has been played successfully in a few games by Black. However, I believe I've found a poisonous continuation.} 8. Bxh6 {For once, we are the ones going for this trade in exchange for damaging Black's pawn structure!} gxh6 {[%csl Rh7,Rh6][%cal Rf8a3]} 9. Nc2 {We continue with our typical maneuver.} Bg7 {Black's most common continuation.} (9... fxe5 {This move has been tried in a few games.} 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qa5+ {( The most common 11...Qg5 is well met by 12.Bb5+ Bd7 13.Bxd7+ Kxd7 14.O-O with problems for Black. )} 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 {White is slightly better in this endgame. Next, we want to reinforce the e5-pawn with g3 and f4.}) 10. exf6 Qxf6 (10... Bxf6 11. Be2 {And we are ready to continue with} O-O {and b4 .}) 11. Bb5 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gb5c6,Yc2e1,Ye1d3,Yc2b4,Yb4d3] We are ready to exchange our bishop for the knight at the right moment. This will help us gain control over the important [e5]- and [c5]-squares.' [Nb4]-[d3] and [Nce1]-[d3] are maneuvers we will keep in mind.} O-O 12. O-O {We continue our development.} Bd7 {And now comes:} 13. Nce1 {[%cal Be1d3] The knight is rerouted to the [d3]-square.} (13. Nb4 {is also possible.}) 13... Be8 14. Bxc6 Bxc6 (14... bxc6 15. Rc1 {And Black is doomed.}) 15. Nd3 {[%csl Ge5,Gc5,Re6] With a dominant position.} *

