with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Nc6 {The main move. Black continues their plan of putting pressure against White's center. All the other tries by Black on the fourth move will be explored in a specific chapter.} 5. Nf3 {We develop our knight on its natural square and give more protection to the [d4]-pawn. Now Black can try different moves. The first chapter of the course will examine the main move 5...[Qb6] and we will investigate all the other tries in the second one. The many transpositions from one move order to another will be explained throughout the course.} f6 $5 {This is premature.} 6. Bb5 $1 {[%csl Ge5] The best choice. We are ready to capture on [c6] and get control over the important [e5]-square. If Black captures on [e5], having our knight there would be ideal. But if we are forced to take with the e-pawn, this is still great.} Qb6 {Black wants to force us to capture on [c6].} 7. Bxc6+ {We accept to exchange our strong bishop for concrete reasons.} bxc6 8. O-O {It is already difficult for Black to find a decent move.} Ba6 {Another common move. But not a good one!} 9. Re1 {[%csl Re6] The [e6]-pawn has been weakened by Black's last move.} f5 {This solves the problem of the [e6]-pawn. But the drawback is that this move closes the position even more. Hence, Black's bishops are not very comfortable.} 10. Nbd2 {[%cal Gd2b3] We are ready to continue with [Nb3] next. White has an important positional advantage.} *

