1. e4 {It is difficult to prevent myself from wanting to commentate 'Best by test according to Bobby Fischer' like almost everyone making a course on 1. [e4]. What I can add is that my current project is to provide Chessable readers with a practical repertoire for White based on 1. e4 against Black's four main openings. The goal is to give you effective lines that are easy to learn, while allowing you time to read books or watch videos to improve your middlegame and endgame skills. The first course against 1...e5 has already been published a few months ago and is entitled: Dynamite 1.e4: Gunsberg Four Knights Game for White.} e6 {The French Defense. This is one of the four main openings to face 1. [e4]. Black invites White to seize the center and a space advantage before counterattacking it with breakthroughs such as ...[c5] and ...[f6] at some point. Even though modern engines don't always like the French because of the space advantage conceded to White, the opening gives many chances for Black to play for a win. Statistics often show that amateurs with White pieces can struggle to navigate French positions even though the engines like their position better. Hence, the French Defense is a great opening to add to your arsenal if you play below the master level. My goal with this course will be to provide you with a simple weapon to learn that will help you pose practical problems to your opponents and where both engines, practical evaluation, and statistics are with White.} 2. d4 {We gladly put a second pawn in the center.} d5 {Black continues with their plan and claims some control over the center.} 3. e5 {The advance variation. We grab space and restrict Black's light-squared bishop before their pawns. One of the main objectives for Black will be to find a way to activate this infamous 'French bad bishop' later in the game. The central pawn structure has been clarified and both sides know where they will concentrate their play. Black will counterattack the center with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Qb6 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Yc8d7,Yd7b5] Black delays the development of the [b8]-knight. This move is usually played first to solve the French bishop issue with a quick ...[Bd7]-[b5].} 5. Nf3 {We continue our development and are waiting for Black to show their cards.} Bd7 {[%csl Rd7,Gf1][%cal Rd7b5] 5...[Nc6] would transpose into our mainline. As mentioned previously, Black's idea is to solve the problem of the French bishop as quickly as possible.} 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Rd7b5,Ga3b5] It is also possible to go on [a3] with our good friend here. It also has the benefit of preventing the ...[Bb5]-idea. For instance, the game could continue:} cxd4 {[%cal Rf8a3] The logical follow-up. Black wants to take advantage of what they see as a 'misplaced' knight. Other moves will transpose to lines we already explored via a different move order.} 7. cxd4 Bxa3 {[%csl Gc1] Black takes on [a3] to damage our pawn structure. However, the drawback is that this capture concedes White all the dark squares and opens the b-file for the [a1]-rook.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Ba1b1,Gf1d3]} Ne7 9. Bd3 {[%cal Ga1b1,Ge1g1] We continue our development by putting the bishop on his best diagonal. At the same time, this move helps to prepare both [O-O] and [Rb1].} Nbc6 {[%csl Rd4] The most common move. Black wants to put pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} 10. Rb1 Qa5+ {And we transpose to a line covered in the first chapter, where we have seen that White can continue with either 11. Bd2 or 11. Kf1.} *

