with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Qb6 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Yc8d7,Yd7b5] Black delays the development of the [b8]-knight. This move is usually played first to solve the French bishop issue with a quick ...[Bd7]-[b5].} 5. Nf3 {We continue our development and are waiting for Black to show their cards.} Bd7 {[%csl Rd7,Gf1][%cal Rd7b5] 5...[Nc6] would transpose into our mainline. As mentioned previously, Black's idea is to solve the problem of the French bishop as quickly as possible.} 6. Na3 $5 {[%cal Rd7b5,Ga3b5] It is also possible to go on [a3] with our good friend here. It also has the benefit of preventing the ...[Bb5]-idea. For instance, the game could continue:} cxd4 {[%cal Rf8a3] The logical follow-up. Black wants to take advantage of what they see as a 'misplaced' knight. Other moves will transpose to lines we already explored via a different move order.} 7. cxd4 Bxa3 {[%csl Gc1] Black takes on [a3] to damage our pawn structure. However, the drawback is that this capture concedes White all the dark squares and opens the b-file for the [a1]-rook.} 8. bxa3 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Ba1b1,Gf1d3]} Bb5 $2 {A common mistake. Black wants to exchange pieces and reach an endgame with the better pawn structure. But this doesn't work as our bad pawn structure allows us to put our rook on the b-file! Even the strong French Grandmaster Yannick Gozzoli fell for this trap in a Blitz game!} 9. Rb1 {[%csl Rb5,Rb6] Oops! Black has problems on the b-file.} a6 10. a4 {The next moves are forced for both sides.} Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qxa4 12. Qxa4 Bxa4 13. Rxb7 {[%csl Gb7,Re8][%cal Bd2b4,Bb4f8,Yd2c1,Yc1a3] The material is equal but White has the advantage in this position. The rook on the 7th rank is annoying and Black has problems on the dark squares. We will bring our dark-squared bishop on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal via [Bd2]-[b4] or [Bc1]-[a3].} *

