with the pawn break ...[c5] and try to find counterplay on the queenside. White will try to build up an attack on the kingside thanks to their advanced [e5]-pawn.} c5 {Black immediately starts counterattacking the center.} 4. c3 {We reinforce our center.} Ne7 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Be7c6,Yb7b6,Yc8a6] Usually, Black uses this move order to develop the [e7]-knight on [c6] and keep the other one on [b8]. Like this, it is simple for Black to get rid of the French bishop after ...[b6] and ...[Ba6]. However, this plan is time-consuming. If Black doesn't go for the aforementioned plan, we will transpose to our lines anyway.} 5. Na3 $5 {Never change a winning team.} Nec6 6. Nc2 {[%cal Gc2d4] We reinforce the center.} b6 {[%cal Rc8a6] Black wants to exchange their bad bishop via [a6].} 7. Nf3 {We continue our development.} Ba6 {Black lost time to achieve their strategic goal.} 8. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh1h3,Gh3f3,Bf3g5,Yh4h5,Yh5h6] We are starting our initiative on the kingside while Black lost lots of time in the opening to exchange their bishop.} Bxf1 9. Kxf1 {[%cal Gh1h3,Gh3f3,Gf3g5,Bg2g3,Bf1g2,Yh4h5,Yh5h6] The position is closed, so the king is safe on [f1]. If necessary, we will improve it with [g3] + [Kg2]. We have ambitious ideas such as [h4]-[h5]-[h6], [Rh3]-[f3] after [Ng5], etc. Black's position is already complicated to handle.} *

